04819nam a22008055i 9781487529666DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20212021onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875296667 a10.3138/97814875296662doi  a(DE-B1597)596746  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aB995.F334bE45 2021 7aREL0510002bisacsh04a181/.0622300aEmil Fackenheim’s Post-Holocaust Thought and Its Philosophical Sources /ced. by Kenneth Hart Green, Martin D. Yaffe. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Kenneth Michael Tanenbaum Series in Jewish Studies : 420 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecognized as one of the leading philosophers and Jewish thinkers of the twentieth century, Emil Ludwig Fackenheim has been widely praised for his boldness, originality, and profundity. As is well-known, a striking feature of Fackenheim’s thought is his unwavering contention that the Holocaust brought about a radical shift in human history, so monumental and unprecedented that nothing can ever be the same again. Fackenheim regarded it as the specific duty of thinkers and scholars to assume responsibility to probe this historical event for its impact on the human future and to make its immense ramifications evident. In Emil Fackenheim’s Post-Holocaust Thought and Its Philosophical Sources, scholars consider important figures in the history of philosophy – including Kant, Hegel, Heidegger, and Strauss – and trace how Fackenheim's philosophical confrontations with each of them shaped his overall thought. This collection details which philosophers exercised the greatest influence on Fackenheim, and how he diverged from them. Incorporating widely varying approaches, the contributors in the volume wrestle with this challenge historically, politically, and philosophically in order to illuminate the depths of Fackenheim’s own thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aPhilosophy, GermanxInfluence. 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAuschwitz.  aBuber.  aEmil Ludwig Fackenheim.  aHegel:Strauss.  aHeidegger.  aHolocaust.  aIsrael.  aJewish philosophy.  aJudaism.  aKant.  aRosenzweig.  ahistory of Jewish thought.  amodern philosophers.  aphilosophy.  areligion.  atheology.1 aBernstein, Jeffrey A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlanchard, Jr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Kenneth Hart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Kenneth Hart, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKavka, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKepnes, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorch, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewell, Waller R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPortnoff, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilford, Paul T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYaffe, Martin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYaffe, Martin D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148752966640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487529666423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487529666/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  